{
  "Alzheimer's disease primarily affects:": "",
  "Vision and hearing only": "",
  "Memory, cognitive function, and eventually all brain functions": "",
  "Voluntary movement and coordination": "",
  "Peripheral nerve sensation only": "",
  "Alzheimer's disease is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that begins with memory loss and cognitive decline and gradually destroys all brain functions, making it the most common cause of dementia worldwide.": "",
  "The hallmark pathological features of Alzheimer's disease include:": "",
  "Excessive dopamine production in the basal ganglia": "",
  "Excess myelin production and enlarged ventricles only": "",
  "Amyloid-beta plaques and neurofibrillary tangles (tau protein)": "",
  "Loss of Schwann cells in the peripheral nerves": "",
  "Alzheimer's disease is characterized by two key brain pathologies: extracellular amyloid-beta plaques (sticky protein deposits between neurons) and intracellular neurofibrillary tangles (twisted tau protein fibers inside neurons), both of which damage and destroy neurons.": "",
  "Parkinson's disease involves the loss of:": "",
  "Serotonin-producing neurons in the raphe nuclei": "",
  "Dopamine-producing neurons in the substantia nigra": "",
  "ACh-producing neurons in the hippocampus": "",
  "GABA-producing neurons in the cerebral cortex": "",
  "Parkinson's disease results from the progressive death of dopamine-producing neurons in the substantia nigra of the midbrain, leading to dopamine deficiency in the basal ganglia and the characteristic motor symptoms.": "",
  "Epilepsy is characterized by:": "",
  "Gradual paralysis of all limbs": "",
  "Recurrent seizures caused by abnormal, excessive electrical activity in the brain": "",
  "Loss of myelin in the peripheral nervous system": "",
  "Progressive memory loss and personality changes": "",
  "Epilepsy is a chronic neurological disorder characterized by recurrent, unprovoked seizures resulting from abnormal, synchronized electrical discharges by groups of neurons in the brain, which can cause convulsions, loss of consciousness, or other symptoms.": "",
  "An ischemic stroke is caused by:": "",
  "A blood clot or embolus blocking a cerebral artery, cutting off blood supply": "",
  "Rupture of a blood vessel in the brain": "",
  "A bacterial infection of the brain tissue": "",
  "Trauma to the skull": "",
  "An ischemic stroke, which accounts for approximately 87% of all strokes, occurs when a blood clot (thrombus or embolus) blocks a cerebral artery, depriving brain tissue of oxygen and nutrients and causing neuronal death within minutes.": "",
  "Multiple sclerosis (MS) involves:": "",
  "Autoimmune destruction of myelin in the CNS": "",
  "Bacterial infection of the meninges": "",
  "Excess production of dopamine in the brain": "",
  "Degeneration of motor neurons only": "",
  "Multiple sclerosis is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks and destroys the myelin sheath and oligodendrocytes in the CNS, creating plaques of demyelination that slow or block nerve impulse conduction.": "",
  "The cardinal motor symptoms of Parkinson's disease include:": "",
  "Seizures, memory loss, and vision problems": "",
  "Tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia (slow movement), and postural instability": "",
  "Paralysis, numbness, and speech difficulty": "",
  "Headache, fever, and stiff neck": "",
  "The cardinal motor symptoms of Parkinson's disease are remembered by the TRAP mnemonic: Tremor (resting), Rigidity (cogwheel), Akinesia/bradykinesia (slowness of movement), and Postural instability, all resulting from dopamine deficiency in the basal ganglia.": "",
  "ALS (amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, Lou Gehrig's disease) involves:": "",
  "Autoimmune destruction of myelin only": "",
  "Progressive degeneration of both upper and lower motor neurons": "",
  "Loss of sensory neurons only": "",
  "Loss of autonomic neurons controlling the heart": "",
  "ALS is a fatal neurodegenerative disease involving progressive destruction of both upper motor neurons (in the motor cortex) and lower motor neurons (in the brainstem and spinal cord), leading to muscle weakness, atrophy, and eventually respiratory failure.": "",
  "A concussion is classified as a:": "",
  "Mild traumatic brain injury (TBI)": "",
  "Type of stroke": "",
  "Skull fracture": "",
  "Type of seizure disorder": "",
  "A concussion is classified as a mild traumatic brain injury (mTBI) caused by a blow or jolt to the head that causes the brain to move within the skull, resulting in temporary neurological dysfunction including confusion, headache, and memory problems.": "",
  "The FAST mnemonic for recognizing stroke symptoms stands for:": "",
  "Fatigue, Anxiety, Stiffness, Temperature changes": "",
  "Falling, Amnesia, Seizure, Tiredness": "",
  "Fever, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Tremor": "",
  "Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call emergency services": "",
  "FAST is a critical public health mnemonic: Face drooping (one side), Arm weakness (drift), Speech difficulty (slurred), and Time (call 911 immediately), emphasizing that rapid treatment is essential because brain tissue dies rapidly without blood flow.": "",
  "What is meningitis?": "",
  "Inflammation of the meninges (protective membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord), usually caused by infection": "",
  "Degeneration of neurons in the cerebral cortex": "",
  "A benign tumor growing on the surface of the brain": "",
  "Inflammation of the brain tissue itself": "",
  "Meningitis is inflammation of the meninges caused by bacterial, viral, or fungal infection, presenting with the classic triad of severe headache, nuchal rigidity (stiff neck), and fever; bacterial meningitis is a medical emergency requiring immediate antibiotic treatment.": "",
  "What is a hemorrhagic stroke?": "",
  "A stroke caused by a blood clot blocking a cerebral artery": "",
  "Bleeding that occurs only in the spinal cord": "",
  "A temporary interruption of blood flow that resolves within 24 hours": "",
  "A stroke caused by the rupture of a blood vessel in the brain, leading to bleeding into or around brain tissue": "",
  "A hemorrhagic stroke occurs when a weakened blood vessel (often from an aneurysm or hypertension) ruptures and bleeds into the brain tissue (intracerebral) or surrounding spaces (subarachnoid), causing direct tissue damage and increased intracranial pressure.": "",
  "What is neuroplasticity?": "",
  "The brain's ability to reorganize itself by forming new neural connections throughout life, especially after injury": "",
  "The process of replacing dead neurons with new ones": "",
  "The inability of the brain to change after childhood development is complete": "",
  "The physical flexibility of brain tissue": "",
  "Neuroplasticity is the brain's remarkable ability to reorganize its structure and function by forming new synaptic connections, strengthening existing ones, or reassigning functions to undamaged areas, which is the foundation for learning, memory, and rehabilitation after brain injury.": "",
  "What is a traumatic brain injury (TBI)?": "",
  "Brain damage caused by an external mechanical force such as a blow, jolt, or penetrating injury to the head": "",
  "Brain damage caused by autoimmune attack on neurons": "",
  "Brain damage caused exclusively by genetic disorders": "",
  "Brain damage caused only by infections like meningitis": "",
  "A traumatic brain injury is damage to the brain caused by an external physical force, such as falls, motor vehicle accidents, sports impacts, or violence, ranging from mild (concussion) to severe (coma or death), and is a leading cause of disability and death worldwide.": "",
  "What does 'demyelination' mean in the context of neurological disease?": "",
  "The excessive production of myelin causing nerve compression": "",
  "The normal process of myelin formation during development": "",
  "The regeneration of myelin after a nerve injury": "",
  "The pathological destruction or loss of myelin sheaths around nerve fibers, slowing or blocking nerve signal conduction": "",
  "Demyelination is the pathological loss of myelin that insulates nerve fibers, as seen in multiple sclerosis and Guillain-Barre syndrome, which disrupts the normal saltatory conduction of nerve impulses and produces neurological symptoms ranging from numbness to paralysis.": "",
  "What is a transient ischemic attack (TIA)?": "",
  "A migraine headache with visual disturbances such as aura, photophobia, and scintillating scotomas that typically last several hours before resolving": "",
  "A temporary episode of stroke-like symptoms caused by a brief interruption of blood flow to the brain, resolving within minutes to hours without permanent damage": "",
  "A permanent ischemic stroke with lasting brain damage caused by complete occlusion of a cerebral artery resulting in irreversible neuronal death": "",
  "A type of nocturnal seizure that occurs exclusively during sleep, involving repetitive abnormal electrical discharges in the temporal lobe cortex": "",
  "A TIA (often called a 'mini-stroke') produces stroke-like symptoms that resolve completely, usually within minutes, because the blood flow blockage is temporary. TIAs are critical warning signs that a full stroke may be imminent and require immediate medical evaluation.": "",
  "What does 'neurodegenerative disease' mean?": "",
  "A progressive disease characterized by the gradual loss of structure or function of neurons, leading to their death": "",
  "A disease caused by infection of the nervous system": "",
  "A reversible condition caused by vitamin deficiency": "",
  "A condition where new neurons grow uncontrollably forming tumors": "",
  "Neurodegenerative diseases are progressive, currently incurable conditions in which neurons gradually deteriorate and die, including Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, ALS, and Huntington's disease, each affecting specific neuronal populations.": "",
  "What is diabetic neuropathy?": "",
  "Spinal cord damage caused by insulin injections near the vertebral column, leading to progressive myelopathy and lower extremity motor deficits": "",
  "An autoimmune condition where chronically elevated blood glucose in diabetes triggers the immune system to attack myelin sheaths, causing multiple sclerosis": "",
  "Peripheral nerve damage caused by chronically elevated blood sugar levels, resulting in numbness, tingling, and pain, usually starting in the feet": "",
  "A condition where chronic hyperglycemia from diabetes stimulates abnormal glial cell proliferation in the central nervous system, leading to brain tumors": "",
  "Diabetic neuropathy is the most common complication of diabetes, caused by chronic hyperglycemia damaging peripheral nerve fibers and their blood supply, leading to a stocking-glove pattern of numbness, burning pain, and weakness starting in the distal extremities.": "",
  "What is the substantia nigra?": "",
  "A region of white matter in the spinal cord": "",
  "A pigmented midbrain structure containing dopamine-producing neurons that degenerate in Parkinson's disease": "",
  "A lobe of the cerebral cortex responsible for vision": "",
  "A type of glial cell found in the brainstem": "",
  "The substantia nigra ('black substance') is a darkly pigmented midbrain structure whose dopaminergic neurons project to the basal ganglia; the progressive death of these neurons in Parkinson's disease causes the characteristic motor symptoms of tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia.": "",
  "What does 'aphasia' mean?": "",
  "Loss of the ability to walk or maintain balance": "",
  "Loss of the ability to swallow food": "",
  "Loss of the ability to see despite intact eyes": "",
  "A language disorder resulting from brain damage that impairs the ability to produce or comprehend speech": "",
  "Aphasia is a language disorder caused by damage to language areas of the brain (typically the left hemisphere), including Broca's aphasia (difficulty producing speech) and Wernicke's aphasia (difficulty understanding language), commonly occurring after stroke.": "",
  "A 72-year-old retired teacher is brought in by her family because she has been getting lost in her own neighborhood, forgetting the names of grandchildren, and leaving the stove on. An MRI shows significant hippocampal atrophy. Which condition is most likely, and why is the hippocampus particularly affected?": "",
  "Epilepsy; repeated temporal lobe seizures have progressively destroyed hippocampal neurons through excitotoxicity, causing both anterograde and retrograde memory loss": "",
  "Multiple sclerosis; progressive demyelination of hippocampal white matter tracts has caused significant hippocampal atrophy, leading to the gradual short-term memory deficits observed": "",
  "Parkinson's disease; the hippocampus is a major center for motor coordination and balance, and dopamine depletion in this region causes the progressive motor and memory symptoms observed": "",
  "Alzheimer's disease; the hippocampus is one of the first regions affected because it is critical for memory formation and is highly vulnerable to amyloid plaques and tau tangles": "",
  "Alzheimer's disease characteristically begins in the hippocampus and entorhinal cortex (memory centers), which is why memory loss is the earliest and most prominent symptom. The hippocampal atrophy visible on MRI reflects the progressive neuronal death caused by amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles.": "",
  "A 63-year-old man presents with a resting tremor in his right hand that disappears when he reaches for objects, along with shuffling gait, masked facial expression, and difficulty initiating movements. His neurologist prescribes levodopa (L-DOPA). How does this medication address the underlying pathology?": "",
  "L-DOPA increases serotonin levels to improve mood and reduce tremor": "",
  "L-DOPA is converted to dopamine in the brain, compensating for the dopamine deficiency caused by substantia nigra neuronal loss": "",
  "L-DOPA blocks acetylcholine receptors to rebalance neurotransmitter levels": "",
  "L-DOPA regenerates the dead dopamine neurons in the substantia nigra": "",
  "Levodopa crosses the blood-brain barrier and is converted to dopamine by the enzyme DOPA decarboxylase in surviving neurons, partially restoring the dopamine levels in the basal ganglia that are depleted due to the death of substantia nigra neurons in Parkinson's disease.": "",
  "A college football player suffers his third concussion in two years. His parents are concerned about long-term brain damage. The neurologist explains the concept of chronic traumatic encephalopathy (CTE). What is the primary concern with repeated concussions?": "",
  "Repeated concussions can cause cumulative brain damage with progressive buildup of abnormal tau protein, leading to CTE with cognitive decline, behavioral changes, and dementia": "",
  "The main concern is skull fractures, not brain damage": "",
  "Concussions only cause temporary symptoms and never have long-term effects": "",
  "Each concussion makes the skull bones thinner and more fragile": "",
  "Repeated concussions can cause cumulative damage with progressive accumulation of abnormal tau protein (similar to Alzheimer's tangles), leading to chronic traumatic encephalopathy (CTE), a degenerative condition causing memory loss, mood disorders, progressive dementia, and behavioral changes.": "",
  "A 28-year-old woman with multiple sclerosis reports that her symptoms worsen dramatically when she takes a hot bath or exercises vigorously. Her neurologist explains this is called Uhthoff's phenomenon. Why does heat worsen MS symptoms?": "",
  "Elevated temperature further impairs nerve conduction in already demyelinated fibers, because damaged nerves are more sensitive to heat-induced conduction block": "",
  "Heat causes the blood-brain barrier to break down": "",
  "Heat activates the immune system to attack more myelin": "",
  "Heat causes new areas of demyelination to form immediately": "",
  "In MS, demyelinated nerve fibers are already conducting poorly; even small temperature increases further slow or completely block conduction in these damaged fibers (Uhthoff's phenomenon), temporarily worsening symptoms. The effect reverses when body temperature returns to normal.": "",
  "A 45-year-old man suddenly develops the worst headache of his life, stiff neck, and vomiting. A CT scan shows blood in the subarachnoid space. The physician suspects a ruptured cerebral aneurysm. What type of stroke is this, and why is it a medical emergency?": "",
  "Ischemic stroke; the clot needs to be dissolved with tPA within 4.5 hours": "",
  "Subarachnoid hemorrhagic stroke; the bleeding increases intracranial pressure, can cause vasospasm, and may lead to rapid death without emergency intervention": "",
  "Transient ischemic attack; symptoms will resolve on their own within 24 hours": "",
  "Meningitis; the blood is actually infected cerebrospinal fluid": "",
  "A ruptured cerebral aneurysm causes subarachnoid hemorrhage, a type of hemorrhagic stroke. The 'thunderclap headache' is characteristic. This is a medical emergency because the bleeding raises intracranial pressure, irritates the meninges, can cause delayed vasospasm, and has a mortality rate of approximately 50%.": "",
  "A medical student is observing a patient with ALS who has progressive muscle weakness and wasting but intact sensation, cognition, and eye movements. The attending physician explains that ALS selectively destroys motor neurons. Why are sensation, cognition, and eye movements typically spared?": "",
  "The patient is on medication that protects sensory neurons": "",
  "ALS actually affects all neurons equally; the student is simply observing an early stage": "",
  "ALS selectively destroys upper and lower motor neurons while sensory neurons, cognitive areas, and the cranial nerves controlling eye movement are typically resistant to the disease process": "",
  "Sensation is maintained by the autonomic nervous system which is never affected": "",
  "ALS specifically targets upper and lower motor neurons, causing progressive paralysis, while sensory neurons, cognitive functions, and the oculomotor neurons (CN III, IV, VI) are largely resistant to degeneration, leaving patients cognitively aware but progressively trapped in a non-functioning body.": "",
  "A child is brought to the emergency department with high fever, severe headache, stiff neck, and a petechial (purple-spotted) rash. The physician immediately starts IV antibiotics before even confirming the diagnosis. Why is this aggressive approach justified?": "",
  "All children with fever should receive antibiotics regardless of diagnosis": "",
  "The antibiotics are being given to prevent a secondary infection only": "",
  "The presentation suggests bacterial meningitis (likely meningococcal), which can be fatal within hours if antibiotics are delayed, so treatment must begin immediately": "",
  "The physician suspects viral meningitis, which requires immediate antiviral treatment": "",
  "Bacterial meningitis, especially meningococcal meningitis (indicated by the petechial rash), can progress to septic shock, multi-organ failure, and death within hours. Immediate empiric antibiotic therapy is critical because waiting for confirmatory test results could cost the patient their life.": "",
  "A stroke rehabilitation therapist is working with a patient who lost the ability to move his right arm after a left-hemisphere stroke three months ago. Over weeks of intensive therapy, the patient gradually regains partial arm movement. What neurological principle explains this recovery?": "",
  "The right hemisphere has grown a new motor cortex": "",
  "The dead neurons in the left hemisphere have regenerated": "",
  "Neuroplasticity allows undamaged brain areas to reorganize and take over some functions of the damaged area through formation of new neural pathways": "",
  "The muscles have learned to move without any neural input": "",
  "Recovery after stroke relies on neuroplasticity, where undamaged brain regions (including surrounding cortex, the opposite hemisphere, and subcortical areas) form new synaptic connections and reorganize to assume some functions of the damaged area, especially when stimulated by intensive, repetitive rehabilitation therapy.": "",
  "A 16-year-old with newly diagnosed epilepsy asks why her seizure medication makes her feel drowsy. The physician explains that the drug enhances GABA activity in the brain. How does this mechanism both control seizures and cause drowsiness?": "",
  "GABA is the main inhibitory neurotransmitter; enhancing it reduces the excessive neuronal firing that causes seizures but also broadly reduces brain excitability, causing drowsiness as a side effect": "",
  "GABA is an excitatory neurotransmitter, so enhancing it speeds up brain activity to override seizures": "",
  "The medication targets GABA in the muscles to reduce convulsions, and drowsiness is an unrelated side effect": "",
  "GABA enhancers stimulate the sleep center in the hypothalamus directly": "",
  "Anti-seizure medications that enhance GABA (like benzodiazepines and barbiturates) increase inhibitory tone throughout the brain, which suppresses the abnormal excessive neuronal firing causing seizures but also broadly dampens normal brain excitability, resulting in sedation and drowsiness as a common side effect.": "",
  "A patient who suffered an ischemic stroke arrives at the ER within 2 hours of symptom onset. The emergency physician decides to administer tPA (tissue plasminogen activator). Why is the timing of this treatment critical, and what is the treatment window?": "",
  "tPA repairs damaged neurons and works best after 12 hours when inflammation subsides": "",
  "tPA dissolves the blood clot blocking the cerebral artery and must be given within 4.5 hours of symptom onset because brain tissue dies progressively every minute without blood flow": "",
  "tPA can be given anytime within 24 hours; timing is not important": "",
  "tPA prevents future strokes but does nothing for the current one regardless of timing": "",
  "tPA is a thrombolytic ('clot-busting') drug that must be administered within 4.5 hours of ischemic stroke onset. The phrase 'time is brain' reflects that approximately 1.9 million neurons die every minute during a stroke, so earlier treatment preserves more brain tissue and leads to better outcomes.": ""
}